text: hi everyone anthony fantano here the
internet's busiest
music nerd and it is time for a review
of the new
lil techa project virgo world
this is the debut commercial album of
new york rapper and singer
lil teca who broke with some big singles
back in 2018 and 2019 with the
lyrical lemonade endorsed ransom going
platinum
multiple times his debut mixtape we love
uteka did
impressive numbers too over a million
units however at the time that it
dropped i can't say i really had strong
feelings on it
teca smooth melodic vocal style nasal
timbre and
affection for generic trap beats struck
me as pretty average at the time
maybe it's something that would change
as he grew artistically
however with virgo world things aren't
sounding much different
vocally techa is still one of the most
carbon copy artists i've heard come up
in the past few years
his range is unimpressive his vocal tone
is vaguely whiny
the massive amount of autotune isn't
really doing him any favors either
his flows and melodies in my opinion
don't really stand out in a growing
ocean of
uziverts thuggers and boogies with
hoodies and despite
nav sounding as robotic as he usually
does with his feature on the song
foreign
there is a case to be made at least nav
has a more recognizable voice
his sound his style is more distinct
than tekkas i will say on this record
there are flashes
of potential here and there like with
the intensely fast flows that tekka
jumps on with
the song back it up there's also the
sensual and intimate melodies on take 10
that are quite nice but honestly
the delivery method is off i listened to
this thing just wishing a better
vocalist had handled it
don't know if it's entirely necessary to
explain the nature of the lyrical
content on this project
too it is pretty surface level from
front to back and i'm not saying that
you need
super deep lyrics to catch a vibe or
make a record in this style sound great
you don't but if techa did have great
lyrics to his advantage
that would at least be something that
would make him stand out
in the crowd sadly the moments that
stuck with me on this record the most
were the ones that
often were the most embarrassing like
the track tick tock not only are the
verses on this one horrendously lazy but
the
mess of auto-tuned vocal harmonies just
sounds like a an auditory abortion plus
the track list on this thing is loaded
with these one to two minute
barely a songs most of which feel like
they only exist to fulfill this formula
of
let's just rack up as many streams as
possible on one record
in under an hour put out a shotgun blast
of songs
pray for a hit and look not that you
can't write a good short song there are
lots of great
short songs out there on the internet
many more being made
every day but with so many stacked on
top of each other on one record
it makes the whole thing feel really
breezy and wash rinse repeat
the beat choices on this record i don't
think are any better than they were on
tekka's tape
once in a while there are some surprises
like the ultra clubby royal rumble
the glitzy beat on selection from dj
scheme and skrillex
hits pretty hard too but teca is almost
buried in it
look for the most part the beats on this
thing just sound like
spotify rap caviar playlist filler one
more surprise that techa packs
into this track list is the number of
songs that lean
in a more dancehall direction which is a
pretty exciting prospect given tekka's
jamaican roots
but his attempts to cross over into this
sound feel no more significant than your
average pop friendly trapper
hopping onto a trend that drake helped
snowball years ago
for me the closest thing to an endearing
banger on this entire project was
miss me the groove and beat sunny synths
and heartening vocals
all of which paints teka in this very
tender happy-go-lucky light that i think
fits him well
a stark contrast from the dull muted
musings on
club minutia and feeling underestimated
on the song closest to heaven or
the other completely unremarkable tracks
on the rest of the record
overall is virgo world one of the worst
things i've heard in 2020
i don't think so but simultaneously it's
so shockingly
underwhelming and non-specific it's
like a slog to listen to because i'm
just desperate for something
interesting to happen feeling a light
too decent three
